name: Magic Johnson
description: It’s the greatest rivalry in professional sports for a reason. Down by a single point in the closing seconds of Game 4 of the 1987 NBA Finals, was there ever a doubt who would play the role of hero for the Los Angeles Lakers? En route to his third Finals MVP award, Johnson makes the impossible look routine, securing an inbound pass in a hostile Boston Garden. After a quick pump fake in the corner, the 12-time All-Star puts the ball on the floor, maneuvering his way into the lane to unfurl a flawless baby hook shot despite the efforts of three Boston Celtics defenders attempting to deny the iconic moment. The dagger – instantly immortalized as the joyful superstar’s ‘junior junior skyhook’ – sealed the Lakers’ 107-106 victory, giving them a commanding 3-1 series lead in the ultimate series. Five days later Johnson would secure his fourth of five championship rings - and his final championship victory over his longtime rival.

name: Invention of the World Wide Web
description:
March 12, 1989: An English scientist named Tim Berners-Lee submitted a proposal for what would become the World Wide Web and forever change the world. 

It all began with a simple question. While working for CERN, Europe's preeminent physical research laboratory, in early stages of what would become the Large Haldron Collider, Berners-Lee pondered: "How will we ever keep track of such a large project?" His solution - laid out in a memo to his boss - was to allow documents to link to one another no matter who wrote them or which computer they were stored on. It would enable people to find information "sometimes without knowing what [they are] looking for." 

Berners-Lee's boss's initial response: "Vague but exciting." 

Exciting indeed. The moment the memo, entitled "Information Management: A Proposal," hit his boss's desk, it set in motion technological advancements that would bring a nearly limitless supply of information to billions of people and transform daily life in much of the world. 

The proposal gained momentum within CERN, and Berners-Lee spent the next two years writing the core protocols that still define the World Wide Web, and which you likely interact with daily: HTTP, HTML, and UDI (later known as URL and URI). CERN open-sourced the code in 1993, which gave rise to the consumer internet industry and the popular websites we use today. 

So while both the computer and internet were momentous in connecting people and information, it was arguably the World Wide Web that brought it all together to really change the world. Berners-Lee's invention made the instantaneous sharing of large swaths of information possible for the first time ever - and, without it, you very well might not be reading this. 

Artwork: Brett Ferdock, Mark Amadio, and Agne Jurkenaite / CNN

name: Ted Turner Launches CNN
description:
June 1, 1980: Media maverick Ted Turner launches the world's first 24-hour TV news network, CNN, and revolutionizes the way news is reported and audiences are informed about the world. 

In a speech broadcast before CNN's first moments, Turner unveiled his vision for the "great step forward in communications." The network was a high-stakes bet by a mogul known for his big business gambles. It paid off. CNN smashed old notions of news from the start, and audiences quickly came to expect to see news around the world as it was happening.
